1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Atmospheric dust deposited in polar ice records the aridity and wind strength of distant) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (continents. We present a high-resolution dust-flux profile from a newly recovered West) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (Antarctic core spanning the last glacial termination. The record shows that the decline in) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (southern-hemisphere dust at the end of the ice age was not gradual but stepped, with two) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (abrupt drops separated by a millennial pause, implying that the atmospheric reorganisation) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (of deglaciation proceeded in discrete jumps rather than a smooth ramp.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Ice cores are layered diaries, and dust is one of their most legible inks. The quantity of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (wind-blown mineral dust trapped in each annual layer reflects how dry, windy, and exposed) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (the source continents were when that snow fell. Reading a dust profile is therefore a way of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (reconstructing the circulation of an ancient atmosphere.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (We report on a core recovered from a high-accumulation site in West Antarctica, chosen) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (because rapid snowfall preserves fine temporal detail. Our focus is the last glacial) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (termination, the transition out of the most recent ice age, when southern-hemisphere dust) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm (loading fell by roughly an order of magnitude.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 402.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (Core Recovery and Dating) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (The core was drilled to bedrock and recovered in metre-long segments kept continuously) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (frozen during transport. Annual layers were counted visually and confirmed by the seasonal) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (cycling of chemical tracers, giving a timescale with uncertainty of a few decades across the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (interval of interest.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (Dust was measured both as particle count, using a laser instrument scanning the melted core,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (and as the concentration of a characteristic crustal element. The two measures agreed) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (closely, which gives us confidence that the structure we report is a feature of the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm (atmosphere and not an artefact of one method.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 244.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 226.0 Tm (A Stepped Decline) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (The central result is that the termination dust decline came in two distinct steps. An) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (initial sharp drop reduced dust flux by about half over a span shorter than our dating) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (resolution can fully separate, implying a change measured in decades to a century. This was) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm (followed by a plateau lasting close to a thousand years, during which dust held roughly) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (steady.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (A second, equally abrupt drop then brought dust flux down to its full interglacial baseline.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm (The intervening plateau is the novel feature; earlier, lower-resolution records smeared the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm (two steps into a single ramp and missed the pause entirely.) Tj
